704. Binary Search
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int low=0;
        int high=nums.size()-1;
       
        while(low<=high)
        {
            int mid=low+(high-low)/2;
           
        
            if(nums[mid]==target)
            {
                return mid;
            }
          else if(nums[mid]<target)
          {
            low=mid+1;
          }
          else{
            high=mid-1;
          }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};


The array is already sorted, so I use the Binary Search algorithm.
I initialize two pointers:
low = 0
high = nums.size() - 1
I continue searching while low <= high.

In each iteration, I calculate the middle index:

mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

This avoids integer overflow.

If nums[mid] == target, I return mid.

If nums[mid] < target, I search the right half by setting:

low = mid + 1;

Otherwise, I search the left half by setting:

high = mid - 1;
If the loop finishes without finding the target, I return -1.
Time Complexity: O(log n) because the search space is halved in every iteration.
Space Complexity: O(1) because only a few variables are used.
